The defendant Lee Dominique Holton was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of Cocaine/Coca, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(c).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Defendant did not respond to staff attorney's letter dated 2/1/17 or satisfy financial obilgations for purposes of expungement.  Expungement will not be processed until defendant fully satisfies his financial obligations in this case.  Paperwork filed without further action at this time.
Letter to defendant indicating that DNA surcharge must be paid before the record of this case may be expunged.
Received and Filed:  Certification of Successful Completion of Sentence Without New conviction for Expungement

Defendant Lee Dominique Holton in court with attorney Robert J Hampton.  Defendant Lee Dominique Holton in custody.  Taylor L. Kraus appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Deputy court clerk:  vk  State has satisfied victim notification.    Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, elements and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Defendant further advised that if he/she is not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found the defendant guilty. Judgment of conviction entered.
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant.
The Court sentenced the defendant to serve 30 days in the House of Corrections CONCURRENT to any other sentence with 4 days credit for time served.
All court costs, fees, and assessments are waived by the court due to defendant's indigency.
Court imposed DNA surcharges to be paid by 10/11/2017 to convert to a civil judgment with tax intercept and collection by other means.
Filed:  
Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief
Pre-trial Incarceration Credit

*
Court finds the defendant was under the age of 25 at the time of the offense, the charge is a misdemeanor, society would not be harmed and the defendant would benefit by expungement.  Court grants expungement upon successful completion of the sentence.
